author: anoek
message:
Fix clock state reset issue

I'm pretty sure this fixes #354

Problem was we were setting two timers for updateClock because of an
update loop stemming from a reaction to our emitted event (which would
finish evaluating before the assignment of our setTimeout), so after
awhile that method could be called with an old clock object and reset
things in a funky way.

This patch also includes a fix for how often to call the clock update
function, we were stomping a common timer value so it wouldn't always
update right on the second as we desire.

  processing the last sync.

  were writing the last value for a key

author: BarneyStratford
message:
Fix for bug #64.
The problem was that the machine decides which player to make as the opponent by comparing the relevant player to black and to white, displaying whichever player is not the relevant player. Unfortunately, the "relevant player" was being set as the currently logged-in user rather than the player whose profile was being viewed. This caused the display of the wrong opponent in about half of cases.
To fix this, GameLists and GobanLineSummaries no longer have an opponentStyle property, and instead take an optional player property. If the player is undefined or not in the game, then the GameList will list Black and White players. If the player is in the game, then it will display only an Opponent player, which is the player that is not given in the player property.

and remove dead stones. Making it so we don't use the stone removal
code logic while setting up a review solves this.

Fixes #67
Fixes #186

author: BarneyStratford
message:
When a user types into a private chat, the recipient receives the chat in their chat window, and also gets a notification from the browser. If the profanity filter is switched on, then it is applied to the contents of the chat window but not to the notification. This commit applies the filter to the notification as well.
On inspection, there was a bug in the English profanity filter itself. Under certain circumstances it would censor the shortest matching profanity when a longer one also matched. The regex has been altered to correct this.
There were a number of words that are extremely offensive in British English that weren't covered by the regex, so I have added them in.

author: BarneyStratford
message: Configuration changes to assist with my setup, and may be of use to other developers on macOS. The macOS Finder liberally spews .DS_Store files all over every filesystem it touches, so these are .gitignored. I get an error message that the "excludes" property of the tsconfig.json file is in conflict with the "files" property. According to https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/tsconfig-json.html, all the files mentioned in the "excludes" property are excluded by default anyway, so their removal should make little difference.

author: benjaminpjones
message:
ngettext: Don't use plural translation for singular counts and vice versa.

ngettext was a little too smart, causing "1 day" to be translated to "1 days" in durationString() because "%s days" was in the catalog, but not "%s day".  Since there is no English project at translate.online-go.com, there was no way to fix this besides changing "%s day" to "1 day", which causes potential issues with interpolate().

author: benjaminpjones
message:
Slim down the prettier config.

Heavily configuring Prettier is discouraged, and many of these settings were default anyway.

Reasoning for keeping the 3 settings:

- tabWidth: ESLint and TSLint before that enforced 4 spaces, so changing to 2 would change every line in the codebase.
- trailingComma: default is ES5, but since we are in a TypeScript environment, modern conventions are possible.
- printWidth: While 80 is generally recommended, this repo has heavily indented passages which look horrible on 80.  Hence a wider setting was chosen.  See https://github.com/online-go/online-go.com/pull/1593/files#r777484939

author: BarneyStratford
message:
Fix bug #189 that caused rankings to display incorrectly
Each player's profile page displays the rankings of the players using a progress bar style UI element with a number indicating the progress. When the progress is less than 50%, then the number is supposed to be displayed to the right of the progress bar, whereas for more than 50% the number is on top of the progress bar. This ensures that the number doesn't overflow the progress bar element.
In the first case (<50% progress) the bar was invisible. This commit fixes that.

author: BarneyStratford
message: I believe I've nailed the bug that causes the number of players in a game to be different to the number of players listed. It was caused by the GameChat object subscribing to the wrong chat_proxy. The Game object can initially contain the wrong game_id. The game_id gets corrected at a later stage, but after the GameChat has initialised. I corrected this by making the user count follow the method used by the user list.

author: felixthelucas
message:
Updated profanity_filter.ts

Updated the lists of filtered words and expressions for the German, Italian and Portuguese languages.

The German list is now in alphabetical order, a repeated entry was suppressed, a few unnecessary words were removed and one included according to smurph's suggestions at the Online Go Forum.

The updated Italian list was provided by lysnew, also at the forum.

I updated the Portuguese list myself: removed unnecessary entries and included more commonly used words and expressions plus their usual variations—since some of them include diacritics, I also enabled the u flag in the regular expression.

More information: https://github.com/online-go/online-go.com/issues/756

author: anoek
message:
Per-user keyed player notes

This ensures that when you log in as a different user, or are not logged
in, you don't see notes from another account.

While there's a loose idea that should be firmed up regarding keying all
data and preferences with the user id, I have a nagging suscpicion that
we'll want still have these keyed to make our lives easier when it comes
to transitioning data and preferences to those keyed values, and dealing
with what do we do when we change accounts and transition from being
logged out to logged in and vise versa.

This PR stacks on top of #1462

message:
Fix for #444.
Sometimes the backend uses an integer for the player.rating.professional field, and sometimes it uses a boolean. React displays integers literally, but treats false or null as a signal to not render the component. Hence, if the backend sends a zero to indicate that the player is not a professional, then that zero gets displayed literally.

author: benjaminpjones
message:
Preserve type when using dup()

This commit changes the siganture of dup() from `dup(obj: any) : any` to `dup<T>(obj: T) : T`.  Since we know the result of dup should be a copy of obj, it makes sense that the return type should be the same as the type of obj.

This may have uncovered a bug in PuzzleEditing where nonexistent members of PuzzleCongig were referenced.

author: anoek
message:
Updated image resizer code to use webp and have a file size limit

This is a workaround to fix #2406 where a chrome behavior (I say bug)
causes a fetch error to occur if our resized files are larger than
64KiB. All resources I've found on the topic do not mention any such
limit and it's unclear to me why this limit is being imposed, so it
may be a temporary issue in Chrome or it may be something else that I'm
not aware of. Regardless, the change to webp largely resolves the issue,
and scaling images down if they are "large" is a fine solution too I
think, so I think the resulting workaround is a desirable behavior
regardless.

author: jreut
message:
Make WebAssembly feature detection more robust

When running Chromium with WebAssembly disabled, the `WebAssembly`
global is still defined, and so a `typeof` check isn't quite enough.
Instead, let's try to allocate a Memory region. This operation will
fail with `RangeError` if WebAssembly is disabled.

See: https://github.com/openbsd/ports/blob/77b70736cf794ac0ff7c420e4321017471799f6d/www/chromium/files/chrome#L57

author: anoek
message:
Update PlayerAutocomplete to hook style and fix overzealous complete triggering

Prior to this update PlayerAutocomplete would fire constantly if there
was a player that matched, this is inconvenient when you're using the
input field for a heavy query (such as searching for player games on the
player profile page). Now the behavior is such that we only trigger when
a user selects a user explicitly, presses enter, or blurs out of the
input field.

I also ported this to be a React hook and added a lot of typings.

explorer, at that time hopefully we can support sibling branch
navigation.

author: benjaminpjones
message:
Return a lowercase string from durationString.

Most, if not all, calls to durationString are followed by toLowerCase().  This causes difficulty in German translation because nouns are always capitalized regardless of location in the sentence.  This commit allows translators to control the capitalization of the time words "week", "day", "hour", "minute" and "second".

In addition, the internals of durationString() have been updated to allow for re-ordering of the units, as might be the case in right-to-left languages.  This puts a higher workload on the translators, but gives more flexibility.

author: anoek
message:
Have eslint run our prettier checks

Having eslint run our prettier checks gets us some prettier output in
our gulp build loop window so we know when prettier is failing before a
commit.  The gulp-prettier plugin seemed to do the same but with less
information (no line numbers for instance, although I assume I just
didn't have it configured right), and overall it was slower, probably
because it had to run a full prettier check after a full eslint check,
and either eslint's caching is applied to the prettier checks when
eslint does it, or it's run in parallel, or both, I'm not sure - but
this seemed to be the better option, but I'm open to being corrected.

Note, I did need to change some code to fix type errors.  One seemed like an obvious, but benign, bug:

{ pause_on_weekends: default_time_options[speed].pause_on_wekends }
                                                 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The other was changed to agree on type, but should not functionally affect anything:

- Object.assign(..., data.get("key", {}), ...)
+ Object.assign(..., data.get("key"), ...)

Since Object.assign ignores undefined sources anyway, there is no need to provied {} as a default.

message:
Fix middleclick board opening issues on Chrome

Apparently not receiving click events on Chrome for middle clicks is now
intended behavior. As a result, we have to start using onMouseUp to
capture them in most cases, though we also need to use onClick for other
cases still as iOS safari doesn't always seem to work with onMouseUp as
desired.

Fixes #174. Probably breaks other stuff, we'll find out.

author: BarneyStratford
message:
Make the data cache use the new serialisation framework.
This allows us to capture more complex kinds of data in the data cache, such as instances of classes. It also allows us to perform validation when the data is loaded, and therefore to prevent corrupt data from bringing the entire system crashing to a halt. I have seen instances where people have had to clear their data cache to get it working again.

author: sinking-point
message:
Fix mid-word line breaks in PaginatedTables

Lines frequently broke mid-word on pages like /groups and /puzzles. This was due
to the word-break property being set to break-all. This commit fixes the issue
by removing the setting of this property. word-wrap is still set to break-word,
so extremely long words should still break.
